\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Gumpinger2018:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Itemize
Deviations for a high number of markers, especially in the range of intermediate
 to high p-values, indicate the presence of confounders that artificially
 inflate the p-values (e.g., Fig.
 3a).
 This inflation can be caused, for example, by population structure or cryptic
 relatedness among the individuals.
 As mentioned in Subheadings 1.3.1 and 3.4—for population structure—a correction
 needs to be performed in order to avoid reporting false positive results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A common way to assess the degree of population structure in the data is
 to compute the genomic inflation factor λGC [55].
 It describes the deviation of the median of the observed test statistics
 from the median of the expected test statistics.
 Since the distribution of the test statistics under the null hypothesis
 is known (either because there is a closed form representation, or because
 it has been derived empirically using permutation testing), so is its median.
 Considering the assumption that most of the SNPs are not associated with
 the trait, λGC should be close to one if no confounder is present [56].
 If λGC is inflated (larger than 1) or deflated (lower than 1), a correction
 for population structure is recommended to avoid false positives or false
 negatives, respectively.
 The inflation or deflation of p-values can be easily visualized in a Q-Q
 plot (refer
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

