\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
https://www.researchgate.net/post/How_do_I_adjust_the_p_value_of_SNPs-phenotype_as
sociation_study_for_multiple_testing:
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Don't adjust the p values.
 Instead, adjust the threshold below which a p value is considered significant.
 This is the standard practice in genomics.
 The formulat is simple: Multiply the number of genetic markers by the number
 of phenotypes.
 This gives you the number of hypotheses tested.
 Then, divide 0.05 by that number.
 You now have the threshold below which a pa value is considered significant.
 It is much more transparent than adjusting the p itself.
 It may be a bit too conservative if the SNPs are in substantial LD (a problem
 that adjusting the p-value itself doesn't abolish).
 If it is a genome-wide study, where you reasonably expect a very large
 number of true positives (e.g.
 hundreds, such as in genome-wide eQTL searches) the false discovery rate
 (q value) makes much more sense and is much more powerful.
 Q-VALUE is an implementation of the required calculations (http://genomics.princ
eton.edu/storeylab/qvalue/) but I prefer to do mine on an Excel sheet, so
 I can plot the data my way.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

